      • listPermutations

        public static List<List<Edge>> listPermutations(List<Edge> list)
        Generates all possible permutations for a list of edges. Example: If list = (e1, e2, e3), then this function returns ((e1, e2, e3), (e1, e3, e2), (e2, e1, e3), (e2, e3, e1), (e3, e1, e2), (e3, e2, e1)).
        Parameters:
        list - the list of edges
        Returns:
        the list of permutations

      • getInstanceOrNumeric

      • getNamedEntityMap

        public static Map<String,String> getNamedEntityMap(List<Amr> amrs)
        Extracts from a corpus of AMR graphs a map mapping each tab-separated triple of
        1. an AMR concept,
        2. a name for this concept and
        3. the information whether the concept is deleted, left or right of the name in the reference realization
        to the number of times this triple has been observed.
        Parameters:
        amrs - the list of AMR graphs from which the map should be extracted
        Returns:
        the ((instance, name, position) → count) map

      • isContiguous

        public static boolean isContiguous(Set<Integer> s)
        Checks wheter a set of integers is contiguous, i.e. there are some natural numbers takeBestN, m such that the set can be written as {takeBestN, takeBestN+1, takeBestN+2, ..., takeBestN+m-1, takeBestN+m}.
        Parameters:
        s - the set of integers
        Returns:
        whether the set is contiguous

      • getLeftmostContiguous

        public static List<Integer> getLeftmostContiguous(Set<Integer> s)
        Returns the leftmost contiguous subset of a set of integers. For example, if s = {2,3,4,6,8,9,10,11}, this function returns the sequence [2,3,4].
        Parameters:
        s - the set of integers
        Returns:
        the leftmost contiguous subset of s
